  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>AI Storage Boom:</strong> If AI-driven demand for massive, high-speed storage (Enterprise SSDs, high-capacity HDDs) structurally shifts WDC's growth trajectory higher, 15% growth could be too conservative.</li>
    <li><strong>Industry Consolidation:</strong> The memory industry is an oligopoly. If participants exhibit strong supply discipline, WDC could experience a "higher for longer" pricing environment, maintaining high margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Spin-off / Separation:</strong> WDC has explored separating its flash and HDD businesses. Such corporate actions could unlock hidden shareholder value not perfectly captured in a consolidated DCF.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Downturns:</strong> Storage is a commodity. When supply exceeds demand, prices crash, and WDC can quickly burn cash, as seen in FY2023 and FY2024. The model assumes a 5-year smooth recovery, which may not materialize.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Intensity:</strong> Maintaining technological parity in NAND requires immense capital expenditures. A misstep in R&D or factory transitions could permanently impair FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Burden:</strong> With $4.6B in total debt against a volatile cash flow profile, WDC faces higher financial risk during downturns than its peers with cleaner balance sheets.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 11% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">WDC operates in highly cyclical, capital-intensive markets (NAND and HDDs). The volatile cash flows warrant a higher risk premium (WACC) compared to a software or consumer staples company. An 11% required return compensates for this inherent business risk.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is TTM FCF so much higher than historical averages?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The storage industry recently exited a brutal cyclical trough. WDC's TTM FCF reflects a snapback in pricing and demand, driven partly by supply cuts and the AI hardware boom. It represents a peak-cycle or mid-cycle recovery rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is valuing WDC with a DCF reliable given its cyclicality?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Valuing cyclical stocks with a DCF is challenging because projecting a smooth growth rate often misrepresents their actual peak-to-trough reality. A common approach is to use a normalized, mid-cycle FCF figure as the base. We used the TTM figure, acknowledging it reflects a strong recovery phase, and tempered it with a higher discount rate.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

